---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const lastUpdated = new Date('2026-04-19').toLocaleDateString('en-US', {
  year: 'numeric',
  month: 'long',
  day: 'numeric',
});
---

<Base title="Direction">
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="eyebrow">Direction · updated {lastUpdated}</div>
    <h1>What I'm building toward</h1>
    <p class="hero-lede">
      A living page about where my attention is and what the work is really about.
      Rewritten when the answer meaningfully changes, not on a schedule.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <span class="section-label">The thesis</span>
    <p>
      We are a few years into a shift where software is no longer just a tool you pick up and put down.
      It is increasingly something you work alongside. Most AI products still treat this like a chat box problem.
      I think the real answer looks different: ambient, memory-rich systems that accumulate context over time
      and act on your behalf in ways you can inspect and trust.
    </p>
    <p>
      The unsolved layer is not model capability. It is runtime: what happens when the model is wrong,
      when context is incomplete, when sessions span weeks, when multiple agents have to agree on state.
      That is the layer I want to build at.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <span class="section-label">Now · current focus</span>
    <ul class="now-list">
      <li><strong>SleepHub.</strong> Shipping the bedside AI experience at Asleep. Understand what happened during the night, then turn that into useful daytime action.</li>
      <li><strong>Knowledge OS.</strong> A markdown-first personal memory substrate. Files as source of truth, agents as readers and writers. This site is one translated output.</li>
      <li><strong>Agent infrastructure.</strong> Session continuity, multi-agent coordination, runtime contracts, and guardrails encoded into the environment rather than left as prompt folklore.</li>
      <li><strong>Validation surfaces.</strong> Exploring how AI systems move from internal prototypes to practical deployment, testbeds, and real users.</li>
      <li><strong>Writing.</strong> Short concrete notes in <a href="/writing">Writing</a>, taken from the workbench rather than from abstraction.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <span class="section-label">Operating principles</span>
    <ol class="belief-list">
      <li>
        <span class="num">01</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Demo-shaped doesn't scale.</strong>
          <p>A prompt that looks impressive once is not a system. What matters is behavior across sessions, failures, interruptions, and edge cases.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="num">02</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Memory should be explicit.</strong>
          <p>If you cannot inspect and edit the memory layer, you cannot really trust it.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="num">03</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Runtime is the product.</strong>
          <p>The happy path is not the interesting part. Product value is realized in retries, state handoffs, partial context, and how the system behaves when things are messy.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="num">04</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Ambient over intrusive.</strong>
          <p>The best software disappears into the workflow. AI should earn its presence quietly.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="num">05</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Deployment matters more than posture.</strong>
          <p>The question is not whether a system sounds impressive, but whether it can survive contact with real operators, real users, and real constraints.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <span class="num">06</span>
        <div>
          <strong>Build in the open when possible.</strong>
          <p>Public artifacts lead to sharper thinking and better systems than private drafts that never meet resistance.</p>
        </div>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <span class="section-label">What I'm not doing</span>
    <p>
      I'm not trying to build another generic agent framework or chase benchmarks for their own sake.
      The attention goes into specific surfaces where AI has to behave well in practice.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
